Angular Momentum

Angular momentum is conserved

Angular Momentum Basics

Definition (Angular Momentum The rotational equivalent of linear momentum; the product of an object's moment of inertia and its angular velocity.).

Where is the moment of inertia and is the angular velocity.

  • Units of angular momentum: kg·m²/s
  • Angular momentum is a vector quantity (direction follows right-hand rule)
  • For a point mass moving in circular motion:

Comparisons to Linear Concepts

Linear Concept Rotational Equivalent
Position Angular position
Velocity Angular velocity
Acceleration Angular acceleration
Mass Moment of inertia
Force Torque
Momentum Angular momentum
Exercise (Identify which of the following objects has the largest angular momentum: ).

A) A 2 kg disk with radius 0.5 m spinning at 10 rad/s
B) A 1 kg disk with radius 1 m spinning at 6 rad/s
C) A 3 kg disk with radius 0.3 m spinning at 15 rad/s
D) A 0.5 kg disk with radius 2 m spinning at 4 rad/s

Calculate the angular momentum for each and compare.

Conservation of Angular Momentum

Definition (Conservation of Angular Momentum If no external torque acts on a system (τₑₓₜ = 0), then the total angular momentum of the system remains constant.).

  • Similar to conservation of linear momentum (when no external forces act)
  • Key principle in understanding many rotational phenomena

Real-World Examples

  • Figure skater pulling in arms during a spin
  • Diver tucking into a ball to increase rotation speed
  • Rotating space objects (planets, stars)
  • Cat righting reflex (how cats always land on their feet)
Exercise (When a figure skater pulls their arms in during a spin, what happens to their: ).

a) Moment of inertia? Smaller
b) Angular velocity? Bigger
c) Angular momentum? Conserved
d) Rotational kinetic energy? Conserved or Less

Explain each answer qualitatively.

AP-Style Problem Analysis

Exercise (AP-Style Question: A student stands on a frictionless rotating platform holding two dumbbells horizontally at shoulder height. Initially, the student and platform are rotating with angular velocity ω₀. When the student lowers the dumbbells to their sides, the angular velocity increases to 1.5ω₀.).

a) Explain why the angular velocity increases when the dumbbells are lowered. b) Calculate the ratio of the initial moment of inertia to the final moment of inertia. c) If the student starts with arms extended and then pulls them in while holding the dumbbells, would the work done by the student increase, decrease, or remain the same compared to lowering the dumbbells? Justify your answer. d) Design an experiment to test the conservation of angular momentum using everyday materials.
